TypeScript is a superset of JavaScript that adds optional static typing to the language. Duck typing, on the other hand, is a dynamic typing technique that focuses on the actual behavior of an object, rather than its explicit type.

With TypeScript, you can declare the type of variables, functions, and objects to help catch type-related errors at compile time. This can make your code more predictable and easier to maintain. For example:

```typescript
let x: number = 5;
```
In this example, the variable x is declared as a number and the compiler will ensure that any operations performed on x will use number-specific functionality.

Duck typing, on the other hand, is a technique where the type of an object is determined by its properties and methods, rather than an explicit type declaration. In other words, if an object has the properties and methods that you expect, it can be treated as if it were of a specific type, even if it is not explicitly declared as such. For example:

```javascript
function printName(person) {
  console.log(person.name);
}
let tom = { name: "Tom" };
let jerry = { name: "Jerry" };
printName(tom); // Outputs "Tom"
printName(jerry); // Outputs "Jerry"
```
In this example, the printName function expects an object with a name property. The objects tom and jerry both have a name property, so they are treated as if they were of the same type, even though they are not explicitly declared as such.

